referenceData.description: Mongoose are a weasel-like animal totaling about 26″ in length with a long, brownish body, short legs and a tail as long as its body. They have small rounded ears and a pointed nose. The mongoose is active during the day and generally sleeps in dens at night
referenceData.impact: Mongoose are opportunistic feeders that will eat birds, small mammals, reptiles, insects, fruits, and plants. They prey on the eggs and hatchlings of native ground nesting birds and endangered sea turtles.

referenceData.description: Pampas grass is an erect giant bunch grass with long, slender, bright green, saw-toothed leaves. At its base are dried, corkscrew-shaped leaves. It has large showy flower plumes that extend 2-3′ beyond the foliage. Two species of pampas grass are found in Hawaii, Cortaderia selloana and C. jubata, which are difficult to tell apart. Both reach heights of 9-10′ and have loosely clumped pinkish-white seed heads. They flower from July through November. Spent flower stalks are sometimes persistent for several years
referenceData.impact: Pampas grass grows rapidly, produces thousands of seeds per flower plume, and can accumulate large amounts of fire prone biomass. Seeds are viable for 4-6 months, but field evidence from Hawaii suggests viability could be greater. It can crowd out native species, impede access, degrade grazing lands, and create fire hazards.

referenceData.description: The coqui is a small tree frog slightly larger than 2.5 cm (1 in) long, with colors varying from light yellow to dark brown. It has a round body shape and a broad rounded snout with obvious toe pads. They also make a distinctive “ko-kee” vocalization that can be easily heard. They are found on ground level and in trees and bushes, but their calls are primarily made from 1-2m (3-7 feet) high
referenceData.impact: No natural predators or competitors to keep populations in check. Populations have reached 55,000 frogs per hectare in some Hawai’i populations (Compared to 24,000 frogs per hectare in their native habitat, Puerto Rico). Eat huge quantities of insects, removing insects from forest floor to treetops. This results in the loss of insect services, such as pollination. Disrupt the balance of vulnerable native ecosystems. Potential food source for snakes if they were to arrive. Loud, incessant and annoying call from dusk until dawn. Adverse economic impacts on tourism. Decreased export plant sales. Disclosure requirement for real estate transactions, has resulted in decreased property values in some locations

referenceData.description: This shrub is semi woody and can grow up to 9′ tall. The young stems are angled and hairy. The leaves are opposite, 3″ long by 1.4″ wide, hairy, and have 5-7 prominent veins. The flowers are pink and have 4 petals with bright yellow anthers. The fruit is cup-like and extremely small. The seeds are very small and numerous.
referenceData.impact: This plant is a prolific seeder and spread by birds. It forms dense stands in pastures and can also invade disturbed forest areas, displacing native species.

referenceData.description: Known as the killer bee, the Africanized Honeybee is uncomfortable around people and animals and will readily depend its hive. They are aggressive and will quickly become upset and sting in greater numbers.
referenceData.impact: The Africanized Honeybee is a public safety threat, particularly in Hawaii, a region that offers a favorable mild climate. It may negatively impact local beekeepers, crop yields and pollination, and local communities and businesses.

referenceData.description: This plant is a large tree fern that can grow up to 40 feet tall. It features long triangular leaves and lacy blades. It has white hairs on stalks, and the trunk does not have thick fibers wrapping around it.
referenceData.impact: This plant spreads quickly. It is fast growing and can outcompete native plants in the forest understory. It threatens slower growing hapuu.

referenceData.description: This plant is a woody shrub that grows into a leafy cactus. Its fragrant flowers vary in smell, and it features round yellow-red berries.
referenceData.impact: It is thorny and overgrows and replaces other plants. It destroys patches of forest and can spread quickly.

referenceData.regStatus: Hawaii Injurious Wildlife, Federal Injurious Wildlife
referenceData.description: This snake ranges in colors from yellowish to dark brown on its back and a cream or yellow underside. It may sometimes have mottled bands. It is noctural and may be found on trees or on the ground. It may grow anywhere from 3 feet long to 9 feet long.
referenceData.impact: The snake feasts on eggs and small mammals. By reducing bug predator populations, crop production may be impacted by pests. It may also cause power outages by climbing power lines.
referenceData.distribution: Currently not established in Hawaii, but have been found in the past

referenceData.description: False kava is a shrub-like plant, ranging from 3 to 6 feet tall with upper branches that extent in a horizontal pattern. The light green lives are large and feature a pinnate vein pattern with unequally lobed bases. They have short hairs along the edge, and when crushed, they may smell like root beer or anise. They may have a red tint to the main vein. It lacks the same medicinal properties as true kava.
referenceData.impact: They displace other plants, and they may threatened the preservation of true kava.

referenceData.description: The stinging nettle caterpillar is the 1st larval form of an Asian moth. It is covered with rows of poisonous spines. The coloration is variable, ranging from white to light grey, with a dark stripe running down the length of the back. Populations peak during the summer months.
referenceData.impact: It produces a painful sting that may induce an allergic reaction. They feed upon and damage crops, including local plants such as ti plants and coconut.

referenceData.description: Chinese Rose Beetles are small, oval-shaped beetles with a metallic green coloration and brown undersides. They have distinctive antennae and feed on the foliage of various plants.
referenceData.impact: Chinese Rose Beetles can cause significant damage to ornamental plants, including roses, hibiscus, and fruit trees, by feeding on leaves and flowers.

referenceData.description: Climbing Fern is a fast-growing vine with wiry stems and delicate green fronds. It forms dense mats that can smother native vegetation and alter ecosystems.
referenceData.impact: This fern poses a serious threat to native ecosystems by displacing native plants and altering habitat structures. It can also increase fire risk and negatively impact water resources.

referenceData.description: Slippery Moss is a non-native moss species that forms dense mats on the forest floor. It has a distinctive bright green coloration and grows in moist, shaded areas.
referenceData.impact: This invasive moss can smother native vegetation, alter soil moisture levels, and disrupt natural ecosystem processes. It poses a threat to native plant diversity and forest health.

referenceData.description: Pakalana is a vine with fragrant yellow flowers that resemble miniature trumpets. It has heart-shaped leaves and climbs over trees and shrubs.
referenceData.impact: Although not considered a high-risk invasive species, Pakalana can escape from cultivation and invade natural areas. It may outcompete native vegetation and alter habitat structures.

referenceData.description: Miconia is a large shrub or tree with broad, dark green leaves and clusters of pink or purple flowers. It can grow up to 50 feet tall and forms dense thickets in forests.
referenceData.impact: Miconia is one of the most serious invasive plant species in Hawaii, threatening native forests and watersheds. It outcompetes native plants, alters habitat structures, and reduces biodiversity.

referenceData.description: Strawberry Guava is a small tree with dark green, glossy leaves and white flowers. It produces small, round, red or yellow fruit that is edible.
referenceData.impact: Strawberry Guava forms dense thickets in native forests, displacing native plants and reducing biodiversity. Its fruit is consumed by birds, spreading seeds to new areas.

referenceData.description: Surinam Cockroaches are large, reddish-brown cockroaches with a glossy appearance. They are winged and primarily nocturnal, hiding in dark, damp areas during the day.
referenceData.impact: Surinam Cockroaches can infest homes and buildings, contaminating food and causing sanitation issues. They can also damage household items and trigger allergic reactions in sensitive individuals.

referenceData.description: Taro Leaf Blight is a fungal disease that affects taro plants, causing dark lesions on leaves and reducing yield. It thrives in warm, humid conditions.
referenceData.impact: Taro Leaf Blight can devastate taro crops, which are culturally and economically significant in Hawaii. Infected plants may experience stunted growth and reduced tuber quality.

referenceData.description: Lantana is a shrubby plant with colorful clusters of flowers that vary in color from yellow and orange to pink and purple. It has a strong scent and grows rapidly.
referenceData.impact: Lantana forms dense thickets that outcompete native vegetation and alter habitat structures. It is toxic to livestock and can reduce grazing land productivity.

referenceData.description: Jackson's Chameleon is a small reptile with a distinctive three-horned crest on its head. It has a green or brown coloration and can change its skin color to match its surroundings.
referenceData.impact: Jackson's Chameleons compete with native species for food and habitat, potentially disrupting local ecosystems. They are also popular in the pet trade, leading to concerns about illegal collection and release.

referenceData.description: Water Hyacinth is a free-floating aquatic plant with glossy green leaves and lavender flowers. It reproduces rapidly and forms dense mats on the surface of water bodies.
referenceData.impact: Water Hyacinth can clog waterways, block sunlight, and deplete oxygen levels, leading to fish kills and habitat degradation. It can also impede navigation and recreational activities.

referenceData.description: Little Fire Ants are tiny ants with a reddish-brown coloration. They have a painful sting and form large colonies in soil, leaf litter, and vegetation.
referenceData.impact: Little Fire Ants can inflict painful stings on humans and animals, causing discomfort and allergic reactions. They also prey on native insects and disrupt ecosystems.

referenceData.description: Krishna Thrips are tiny, slender insects with fringed wings. They feed on a wide range of plants and can cause damage to leaves, flowers, and fruit.
referenceData.impact: Krishna Thrips can reduce crop yields and quality by feeding on plant tissues and transmitting diseases. They are difficult to control and can rapidly reproduce in favorable conditions.

referenceData.description: House Mice are small rodents with pointed noses and long tails. They have fur that varies in color from light brown to gray. They are omnivorous and adapt well to a variety of habitats.
referenceData.impact: House Mice can cause damage to crops, structures, and stored food. They also carry diseases and parasites that can be transmitted to humans and pets.

referenceData.description: Fallow Deer are medium-sized deer with spotted coats that vary in color from light brown to dark brown. They have broad, flattened antlers and a white rump patch.
referenceData.impact: Fallow Deer can damage agricultural crops and native vegetation through browsing and trampling. They compete with native deer species for resources.

referenceData.description: Wild Boar, also known as feral pigs, are large, stocky mammals with bristly coats and tusks. They are highly adaptable and can thrive in a variety of habitats.
referenceData.impact: Wild Boar can damage crops, native vegetation, and archaeological sites through rooting and trampling. They also compete with native species for food and habitat.

referenceData.description: Black Rats are medium-sized rodents with slender bodies, large ears, and long tails. They have fur that varies in color from black to brown. They are excellent climbers and are highly adaptable.
referenceData.impact: Black Rats can damage crops, structures, and stored food. They also carry diseases and parasites that can be transmitted to humans and pets.

referenceData.description: Willow Scale are small insects that feed on the sap of willow trees. They have oval-shaped bodies and are often covered in a white waxy substance. They can reproduce rapidly under favorable conditions.
referenceData.impact: Willow Scale can weaken willow trees by draining their sap. Infestations can lead to stunted growth, branch dieback, and even death of the tree.

referenceData.description: Red Imported Fire Ants are small reddish-brown ants with a painful sting. They are aggressive and form large colonies with multiple queens. They are highly adaptable and can thrive in a variety of habitats.
referenceData.impact: Red Imported Fire Ants can sting humans, pets, and wildlife, causing intense pain and allergic reactions. They also disrupt ecosystems by preying on native insects and outcompeting native ants.

referenceData.description: Pacific House Centipedes are long, flattened insects with multiple pairs of legs. They are typically yellowish-gray with dark bands on their bodies. They are nocturnal predators that feed on insects and other small invertebrates.
referenceData.impact: Pacific House Centipedes are not harmful to humans but may cause alarm due to their appearance. They play a beneficial role in controlling insect populations indoors.

referenceData.description: Himalayan Ginger is a tall, perennial herb with large, lush green leaves and clusters of showy yellow flowers. It can grow rapidly and forms dense stands, outcompeting native vegetation.
referenceData.impact: Himalayan Ginger displaces native plants and alters habitat structure, leading to a loss of biodiversity. Its dense growth can also increase the risk of wildfire.

referenceData.description: Giant Reed is a tall, bamboo-like grass with hollow stems and feathery plumes. It forms dense thickets along streams, ditches, and other waterways, displacing native vegetation.
referenceData.impact: Giant Reed disrupts natural water flow, increases sedimentation, and alters habitat conditions for native species. Its rapid growth can also exacerbate flooding and erosion.

referenceData.description: Yellow Ginger is a perennial herb with long, lance-shaped leaves and clusters of fragrant yellow flowers. It can spread rapidly and forms dense colonies, displacing native vegetation.
referenceData.impact: Yellow Ginger competes with native plants for resources and alters habitat structure, reducing biodiversity. Its dense growth can also impede access to natural areas.

referenceData.description: Banana Poka is a fast-growing vine with distinctive red flowers and round fruits. It can quickly cover and shade out native vegetation, disrupting native ecosystems.
referenceData.impact: Banana Poka forms dense thickets that crowd out native plants and reduce biodiversity. Its rapid growth can also interfere with native forest regeneration.

referenceData.description: Albizia is a fast-growing tree with fern-like leaves and white flowers. It can reach towering heights and form dense stands, shading out native vegetation below.
referenceData.impact: Albizia trees are known for their rapid growth and ability to outcompete native plants. They can also pose a hazard by dropping large branches and causing damage during storms.

referenceData.description: Rapid Ohia Death (ROD) is caused by two species of fungus, Ceratocystis lukuohia and Ceratocystis huliohia, which infect and kill ohia trees (Metrosideros polymorpha), a keystone species in Hawaiian forests.
referenceData.impact: ROD has devastated ohia forests, leading to widespread die-offs and ecosystem disruption. Ohia trees play a crucial role in maintaining watershed health and supporting native biodiversity.

referenceData.description: Devil Weed is a fast-growing shrub with serrated leaves and small white flowers. It forms dense thickets, displacing native vegetation and altering habitat conditions.
referenceData.impact: Devil Weed outcompetes native plants for resources and disrupts native ecosystems. Its rapid spread can also hinder efforts to restore native habitats.

referenceData.description: Banana Poka Moth is a small moth that feeds on the leaves of banana poka vines (Passiflora tarminiana). Its larvae can defoliate the vines, reducing their growth and reproductive capacity.
referenceData.impact: Banana Poka Moth can help control the spread of banana poka vines, which are invasive in Hawaii. However, it can also attack native passionflower species, potentially affecting native ecosystems.
